PCA Analysis

To do PCA, we use prcomp() in R, which uses the SVD method. We demean the matrix and set sd to 1, following conventions of Avellaneda

dt_ts.pc <- prcomp(dt_ts, center = TRUE, scale. = TRUE)

Eigenportfolio analysis

Next, we try to find eigenportfolios by interpreting the elements of our principal component vectors as weights for each cryptocurrency. First, we take the main principal component and construct the eigenportfolio.

Again, following conventions, we divide each element by the standard deviation of the corresponding cryptocurrency, and then left multiply its transpose with our original data matrix.

# Find weighting by dividing by each asset's standard deviation.
sd.ret <- table.Stats(dt_ts)["Stdev",] %>% as.numeric()

# Find sum of components
sum.wgts <- (dt_ts.pc$rotation[,1] / sd.ret)  %>% sum()
sum.wgts
## [1] 97.86727

Notice how values are close to 100. Next, we normalize them so the sum becomes 1.

# Find normalized wgts for principal eigenportfolio
normalized.wgts <- (dt_ts.pc$rotation[,1] / sd.ret) / sum.wgts

cat(normalized.wgts, "\n", "Sum of weights:", sum(normalized.wgts))
## 0.02619561 0.02676977 0.02511184 0.02916153 0.02484262 0.02433871 0.029145 0.0257276 0.02588738 0.034363 0.01692669 0.01443284 0.03048275 0.03152696 0.03459076 0.03242048 0.03206206 0.02823556 0.03040035 0.008488616 0.032715 0.03323665 0.04009895 0.03786824 0.03771214 0.03819564 0.03615895 0.03662394 0.04134356 0.02716513 0.04816442 0.05960725 
##  Sum of weights: 1

Next, we find the returns of this eigenportfolio.

# Convert to matrix form for matrix algebra
nwgts_mat <- matrix(normalized.wgts, nrow = 1)
nwgts_mat <- t(nwgts_mat)

dt_mat <- as.matrix(dt) %>% apply(2, function(x) as.numeric(x))
dt_mat <- dt_mat[,-1]

# Compute eigenportfolio 1 return
egnportfolio1_ret <- dt_mat %*% nwgts_mat
egnportfolio1_ret <- xts(x = egnportfolio1_ret, order.by = as.POSIXct(dt$Date, format = "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S")) 
colnames(egnportfolio1_ret) <- "Eigen Portfolio 1"

# Compare Return with BTC and ETHereum
chart.CumReturns(cbind(dt_ts$ETH, dt_ts$BTC, egnportfolio1_ret),legend="topright", main="Cumulative Returns")

One interesting feature of our “market” factor is that its return seems to be tracking that of Ethereum more than BTC. One reason for this could be that most cryptocurrencies display higher correlation with returns of Etherum vs those of BTC. We do a simple check by looking at the correlation matrix.

cor.ret <- cor(cbind(dt_ts, egnportfolio1_ret))
cor.ret[,c("BTC", "ETH", "Eigen.Portfolio.1")] %>% colSums()
##               BTC               ETH Eigen.Portfolio.1 
##          20.70739          21.87418          24.50165

While this is in no way rigorous, because we know the correlations are all positive across the returns, the sum of correlations across the rows can give us a rough measure of how well correlated each cryptocurrency is with the remaining 29 cryptocurrencies. Thus, as we expect, ETH has a higher sum of correlations, indicating our dataset is biased towards coins that are correlated with Ethereum, which is the usual case.

Now we try to see what the return profile of our remaining portfolios are.

Eigenportfolio2

From principal component 2 and onwards, we see that the elements contain negative values, which makes sense since each principal component must be orthogonal to each other.

Thus, we must deal with the issue of negative weightings. In this analysis, we assume negative weightings imply that investors take a “short-sale” of the corresponding cryptocurrency.

This is a plausible assumption to make, since most cryptocurrencies are easy to short-sell.

Normalization is done by taking the sum of the absolute value of the elements.

# sum of wgts
sum.wgts2 <- (dt_ts.pc$rotation[,2] / sd.ret)  %>% abs() %>% sum()

# Find normalized weights for principal eigenportfolio2
normalized.wgts2 <- (dt_ts.pc$rotation[,2] / sd.ret) / sum.wgts2

# Convert to matrix form for matrix algebra
nwgts_mat2 <- matrix(normalized.wgts2, nrow = 1)
nwgts_mat2 <- t(nwgts_mat2)

# Compute eigenportfolio 1 return
egnportfolio2_ret <- dt_mat %*% nwgts_mat2
egnportfolio2_ret <- xts(x = egnportfolio2_ret, order.by = as.POSIXct(dt$Date, format = "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S")) 
colnames(egnportfolio2_ret) <- "Eigen Portfolio 2"

# Compare Return with BTC and ETHereum
chart.CumReturns(cbind(dt_ts$ETH, dt_ts$BTC, egnportfolio2_ret),legend="topright", main="Cumulative Returns")

We also verify that the Eigenportfolio2 and Eigenportfolio1 are not correlated.

cor(egnportfolio1_ret, egnportfolio2_ret)
##                   Eigen Portfolio 2
## Eigen Portfolio 1      3.721975e-05

Now, we take a look at the risk-adjusted measure, also known as the Sharpe Ratio (we assume a risk free rate of 0% for simplicity).

apply(cbind(egnportfolio1_ret, egnportfolio2_ret, egnportfolio3_ret, dt_ts$BTC, dt_ts$ETH), 2,  SharpeRatio)[1,]
## Eigen.Portfolio.1 Eigen.Portfolio.2 Eigen.Portfolio.3               BTC 
##        0.01925718        0.02858500        0.01669299        0.01914406 
##               ETH 
##        0.02866391

We see that the Sharpe Ratio of eigenportfolio 2 and ETH are very similar, but the correlation between them are near zero. Then, allocating half of our wealth to Eigenportfolio2 and Ethereum should have in theory produced better risk-adjusted returns.

SharpeRatio(0.5 * egnportfolio2_ret + 0.5 * dt_ts$ETH)[1,1]
## [1] 0.03552542

Now, we can go further, since eigenportfolios have zero correlations to each other.

SharpeRatio(0.33 * egnportfolio2_ret + 0.33 * dt_ts$ETH + 0.33 * egnportfolio3_ret)[1,1]
## [1] 0.03848537

We observe that our Sharpe Ratio of diversified portfolio is higher than when we have not diversified.

Practical Implications

Now, this analysis assumes that factors are static. However, that is not true in reality. The probability distribution implied the markets constantly changes, which is dependent on numerous factors. Therefore, to verify that diversifying one’s wealth using the concept of eigenportfolios provides better risk-adjusted returns, we must conduct a rigorous study employing in-sample and out-of-sample data.
